\begin_layout Title
Lecture 8: The New Keynesian Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Dynamics in the New Keynesian Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let me start with the three equation representation of the New-Keynesian
 model.
 The IS equation is the combination of the Euler equation and the goods
 market clearing condition:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
IS:\dot{x}=\frac{i-\pi-r}{\sigma}+\varepsilon^{x}\left(t\right),\label{eq:ISequation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is natural rate produced by the model with flexible prices, possibly a
 time varying rate, 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is a nominal policy rate and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 inflation.
 Then, we have the Phillips curve:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
PC:\rho\pi=\kappa x+\dot{\pi}+\varepsilon^{\pi}\left(t\right),\label{eq:PhillipsCurve}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

both equations will be derived later.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we have the Taylor rule, or any rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
TR:i=i^{*}+\phi\pi+\phi_{x}x+\varepsilon^{i}\left(t\right).
\]

\end_inset

The Taylor rule specifies a target rate 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{*}$
\end_inset

 and two responsiveness coefficients: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \phi,\phi_{x}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In all cases, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{z}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $z\in\left\{ i,x,\pi\right\} $
\end_inset

 represents an deterministic shock.
 We impose only that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\varepsilon^{z}\left(t\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Steady State.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The steady-state of the model is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \dot{x},\dot{\pi}\right\} =\left\{ 0,0\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{ss}=i-r.
\]

\end_inset

Then, for the output gap:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{ss}=\frac{\rho}{\kappa}\left(i-r\right).
\]

\end_inset

Finally, we conclude with:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i-i^{*}=\frac{\phi+\phi_{x}\frac{\rho}{\kappa}}{1-\left(\phi+\phi_{x}\frac{\rho}{\kappa}\right)}\left(i^{*}-r\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A zero inflation, zero gap equation involves is obtained when 
\begin_inset Formula $i=r$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dynamical System Representation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We substitute in Taylor to obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{x}=\frac{i^{*}+\left(\phi-1\right)\pi+\phi_{x}x-r}{\sigma}
\]

\end_inset

and re-arrange the system:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{\pi}=-\kappa x+\rho\pi.
\]

\end_inset

This is the classic, two equation version of the model.
 It's a system of linear first order ODE's.
 It can therefore be written as in matrix form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{X}=AX+B\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\phi_{x} & \phi-1\\
-\kappa & \rho
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

with inhomogeneous block given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B\left(t\right)=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\frac{i^{*}\left(t\right)-r\left(t\right)}{\sigma}-\varepsilon^{x}\left(t\right)+\frac{1}{\sigma}\varepsilon^{i}\left(t\right)\\
-\varepsilon^{\pi}\left(t\right)
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{X}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
\dot{x}\\
\dot{\pi}
\end{array}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Next, we solve the system with two methods.
 First, by substitution and construction of a second-order differential
 equation, Second, by working out a solution in system, following methods
 for systems of linear ODEs.
 There are plenty of methods to do so.
 Some information is contained in Kamien and Schwartz and Seierstad and
 Sydsæter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Solution via method of second-order ODE.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take the time derivative of the PC to yield:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{\pi}-\rho\dot{\pi}+\kappa\dot{x}=\dot{\varepsilon}^{\pi}\left(t\right),
\]

\end_inset

and replace the IS to obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{\pi}-\rho\dot{\pi}+\kappa\frac{i^{*}+\left(\phi-1\right)\pi+\phi_{x}x-r}{\sigma}=-\left(\dot{\varepsilon}^{\pi}\left(t\right)+\kappa\left(\varepsilon^{x}\left(t\right)+\frac{1}{\sigma}\varepsilon^{i}\left(t\right)\right)\right).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 appears again, because of the component in the Taylor rule.
 For this, it is convenient to use the Phillips curve in levels:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\frac{\dot{\pi}+\rho\pi}{\kappa}
\]

\end_inset

in the equation above yields:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{\pi}-\rho\dot{\pi}+\kappa\frac{i^{*}-r+\phi_{x}\left(\frac{\dot{\pi}+\rho\pi}{\kappa}\right)}{\sigma}+\kappa\frac{\phi-1}{\sigma}\pi=0.
\]

\end_inset

Thus, re-arranging terms, we obtain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ddot{\pi}-\rho\left(1-\frac{\kappa}{\sigma}\phi_{x}\right)\dot{\pi}+\frac{\kappa\left(\phi-1\right)+\phi_{x}\rho}{\sigma}\pi=-\left(\dot{\varepsilon}^{\pi}\left(t\right)+\kappa\left(\varepsilon^{x}\left(t\right)+\frac{1}{\sigma}\varepsilon^{i}\left(t\right)+\frac{i^{*}-r\left(t\right)}{\sigma}\right)\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation is of the form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ddot{\pi}+\gamma_{1}\dot{\pi}+\gamma_{0}\pi=h_{0}\left(t\right)\label{eq:fundamental}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{1}=-\rho\left(1-\frac{\kappa}{\sigma}\phi_{x}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{0}=\frac{\kappa\left(\phi-1\right)+\phi_{x}\rho}{\sigma}
\]

\end_inset

and the inhomogeneous block is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h_{0}\left(t\right)=-\dot{\varepsilon}^{\pi}\left(t\right)+\kappa\left(\varepsilon^{x}\left(t\right)+\frac{1}{\sigma}\varepsilon^{i}\left(t\right)+\frac{i^{*}-r\left(t\right)}{\sigma}\right).
\]

\end_inset

A function that satisfies (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fundamental"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) at all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is called the particular solution.
 In general, there are concrete solutions to the particular solution (the
 solution to the homogenous case) when it is a constant, a step function
 or a trigonemetric function, or polynomials.
 The proof is related to the connection between polynomials, trigonemetric
 functions and the exponential.
 This equation can be solved as a system, or directly, by guess and verify.
 For example, to deal with the constant, note that to any solution with
 zero, provided that 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{*}-r\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is also constant and there are no shocks, we could add the constant 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{h_{0}}{\gamma_{0}}
\]

\end_inset

and be done: this would solve the equation at all 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve for the actual path of inflation, we invoke the superposition principle.
 That is, any solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{g}$
\end_inset

 that solves:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ddot{\pi}+\gamma_{1}\dot{\pi}+\gamma_{0}\pi=0\label{eq:general}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

can be added to another solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{p}$
\end_inset

 that solves the fundamental equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:fundamental"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) to produce a path for inflation.
 The equation above, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:general"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, is called general solution.
 A general solution can involve a linear combination of such solutions,
 a particular solution, and any arbitrary number of generic solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{g}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Solving the General Solution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conjecture that the solution to the general solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{g}$
\end_inset

 to the equation is: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K\exp\left(\lambda\right).
\]

\end_inset

Then, we would have that a solution is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\lambda\right)^{2}K\exp\left(\lambda\right)+\gamma_{1}\lambda K\exp\left(\lambda\right)+\gamma_{0}K\exp\left(\lambda\right)=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Canceling terms, we obtain the characteristic polynomial:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{1}=\frac{-\gamma_{1}+\sqrt{\gamma_{1}^{2}-4\gamma_{0}}}{2}=\frac{\rho\left(1-\frac{\kappa}{\sigma}\phi_{x}\right)+\sqrt{\rho^{2}\left(1-\frac{\kappa}{\sigma}\phi_{x}\right)^{2}-4\frac{\kappa\left(\phi-1\right)+\phi_{x}\rho}{\sigma}}}{2}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{2}=\frac{-\gamma_{1}-\sqrt{\gamma_{1}^{2}-4\gamma_{0}}}{2}=\frac{\rho\left(1-\frac{\kappa}{\sigma}\phi_{x}\right)-\sqrt{\rho^{2}\left(1-\frac{\kappa}{\sigma}\phi_{x}\right)^{2}-4\frac{\kappa\left(\phi-1\right)+\phi_{x}\rho}{\sigma}}}{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ignoring the case of equal roots, and the case of imaginary roots, we obtain
 roots of opposite sign if:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\kappa\left(\phi-1\right)+\phi_{x}\rho>0
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi>1-\frac{\rho\phi_{x}}{\kappa}>0,
\]

\end_inset

one of the roots satisfies the Taylor principle.
 Thus, the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{x}$
\end_inset

 relaxes the Taylor principle, but the idea is the same.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Determining the Constants: Indeterminacy and the Taylor Principle.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly the math gets cluttered by the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{x}$
\end_inset

, but it is simplified setting: 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{x}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In the latter case, we have that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{1}=\frac{\rho+\sqrt{\rho^{2}-4\kappa\frac{\phi-1}{\sigma}}}{2}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{2}=\frac{\rho-\sqrt{\rho^{2}-4\kappa\frac{\phi-1}{\sigma}}}{2}.
\]

\end_inset

The theory of ODE's guarantees that no other solutions exist (e.g., Oliver
 and Boyd; also check Kamien and Schwartz).
 Then, it's a matter of finding the right initial conditions to determine
 the weights.
 The general solution is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi^{g}\left(t\right)=K_{1}\exp\left(\lambda_{1}t\right)+K_{2}\exp\left(\lambda_{2}t\right).
\]

\end_inset

Key to the new-Keynesian model, inflation is not a state variable.
 It can jump at any minute—prices are a state variable.
 If inflation can jump, so can consumption and since prices cannot adjust,
 the same is true about output.
 Therefore, we have that we cannot use inflation nor output as initial condition
s.
 Instead, we must use information regarding the terminal condition: a steady-sta
te condition.
 If the central bank wants to target the zero-zero equilibrium, we could
 use this as a terminal condition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let there be only positive discriminants:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho^{2}>4\kappa\frac{\phi-1}{\sigma}.
\]

\end_inset

Clearly, this is true unless 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is too large.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the Taylor principle is violated, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 Then, in that case, at least one of the solutions is negative, and the
 other is positive.
 Our terminal conditions become:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{ss}=0=\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}K_{1}\exp\left(\lambda_{1}t\right)+K_{2}\exp\left(\lambda_{2}t\right)=K_{2}\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\exp\left(\lambda_{2}t\right).
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}>0$
\end_inset

, we immediately have that 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, we can observe that the condition is solved for any 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If the Taylor principle is violated, we have the possibility of multiplicity—in
cluding the possibility of sunspot equilibria that lead to jumps in inflation
 over time.
 In other words, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}<0$
\end_inset

, then we have a problem.
 Since any 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\left(0\right)$
\end_inset

 is a solution, we have that any solution is possible.
 Solutions may even oscillate if further conditions are not met: see Benhabib,
 Schmitt-Grohe and Uribe.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}=0$
\end_inset

, we must always fall in a steady state as an initial condition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the Taylor principle is satisfied, 
