\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\phi>1.
\]

\end_inset

then we have two explosive roots—since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2}>0$
\end_inset

.
 In that case, we have that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\pi\left(t\right)=K_{1}\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\exp\left(\lambda_{1}t\right)+K_{2}\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\exp\left(\lambda_{2}t\right)
\]

\end_inset

must necessarily involve 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{1},K_{2}=0$
\end_inset

 if inflation is to be stationary.
 Hence, the particular solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \pi\left(0\right),\pi'\left(0\right),x\left(0\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is going on? In the new-Keynesian model, inflation is not predetermined.
 Firms can chose to deviate from the zero-zero equilibrium, but the point
 is that this would lead to an implosion or explosion of inflation.
 As long as the Taylor rule is satisfied, we avoid multiplicity, through
 a threat of destruction of the economy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
In-homogeneous Case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are left with finding the solution that includes the 
\shape italic
particular
